One can then calculate observable quantities — such as the weak lensing kernel or the growth rate of structure f (z) — using the parameterized field equations (1.5.13)–(1.5.17). Similarly, they can be implemented in an Einstein-Boltzmann solver code such as CAMB [559] to utilize constraints from the CMB. If we take the divergence of the gravitational field equations (i.e., the unperturbed equivalent of Eq. (1.5.12)), the left-hand side vanishes due to the Bianchi identity, while the stress-energy tensor of matter obeys its standard conservation equations (since we are working in the Jordan frame). Hence the U-tensor must be separately conserved, and this provides the necessary evolution equation for the variable \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
