As we have set the anisotropic stress to zero, the perturbations are fully described by Q. The main problem is therefore to find an explicit expression that shows how Q depends on cs. [785] have provided the following explicit approximate expression for Q (k, a) which captures the behavior for both super- and sub-horizon scales: 1.8.21\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Q(k,a) = 1 + {{1 - {\Omega _{M,0}}} \over {{\Omega _{M,0}}}}{{(1 + w){a^{- 3w}}} \over {1 - 3w + {2 \over 3}\nu {{(a)}^2}}}.$$\end{document} Here \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$v{(a)^2} = {k^2}c_s^2a/({\Omega _M}{,_0}H_0^2)$\end{document} which it is defined through csk ≡ νaH so that ν counts how deep a mode is inside the sound horizon.

Eq. (1.8.21) depends substantially on the value of the sound speed or, to put it differently, on the scale considered. For scales larger than the sound horizon (ν ≈ 0), Eq. (1.8.21) scales as a−3w and for Ωm,0 = 0.25 and w = −0.8 we have that 1.8.22\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Q - 1 \approx {3 \over {17}}{a^{2.4}} \simeq 0.18{a^{2.4}}\,.$$\end{document} This is not a negligible deviation today, but it decreases rapidly as we move into the past, as the dark energy becomes less important.8 As a scale enters the sound horizon, Q − 1 grows with one power of the scale factor slower (since δDE stops growing), suppressing the final deviation roughly by the ratio of horizon size to the scale of interest (as now ν2 ≫ 1). In the observable range, (k/H0)2 ≈ 102–104. Therefore, if cs ≈ 1, Q → 1 and the dependence on cs is lost. This shows that Q is sensitive to cs only for small values, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$c_s^2 \lesssim {10^{- 2}}$\end{document}.

We can characterize the dependence of Q on the main perturbation parameter \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$c_s^2$\end{document} by looking at its derivative, a key quantity for Fisher matrix forecasts: 1.8.23\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{\partial \log Q} \over {\partial \log c_s^2}} = - {x \over {(1 + x)}}{{Q - 1} \over Q}\,,$$\end{document} where \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$x = {2 \over 3}v{\left(a \right)^2}/\left({1 - 3w} \right) \simeq 0.2v{\left(a \right)^2}$\end{document} (with the last expression being for w = − 0.8). For the values we are interested in here, this derivative has a peak at the present epoch at the sound horizon, i.e., for cs ≈ H0/k, which in the observable range of k is cs ≈.01 −.001, and declines rapidly for larger cs. This means that the sensitivity of Q to the sound speed can be boosted by several orders of magnitude as the sound speed is decreased.

There are several observables that depend on Q:

The growth of matter perturbations
There are two ways to influence the growth factor: firstly at background level, with a different Hubble expansion. Secondly at perturbation level: if dark energy clusters then the gravitational potential changes because of the Poisson equation, and this will also affect the growth rate of dark matter. All these effects can be included in the growth index γ and we therefore expect that γ is a function of w and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$c_s^2$\end{document} (or equivalently of w and Q).
The growth index depends on dark-energy perturbations (through Q) as [785] 1.8.24\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\gamma = {{3(1 - w - A(Q))} \over {5 - 6w}}$$\end{document}1.8.25\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$A(Q) = {{Q - 1} \over {1 - {\Omega _M}(a)}}.$$\end{document} Clearly here, the key quantity is the derivative of the growth factor with respect to the sound speed: 1.8.26\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{\partial \log G} \over {\partial \ln c_s^2}} \propto \int\nolimits_{{a_0}}^{{a_1}} {{{\partial \gamma} \over {\partial c_s^2}}{\rm{d}}a} \propto \int\nolimits_{{a_0}}^{{a_1}} {{{\partial Q} \over {\partial c_s^2}}{\rm{d}}a} \propto \int\nolimits_{{a_0}}^{{a_1}} {(Q - 1)\;{\rm{d}}a} \,.$$\end{document} From the above equation we also notice that the derivative of the growth factor does not depend on Q − 1 like the derivative Q, but on Q − Q0 as it is an integral (being Q0 the value of Q today). The growth factor is thus not directly probing the deviation of Q from unity, but rather how Q evolves over time, see [786] for more details.
Redshift space distortions
The distortion induced by redshift can be expressed in linear theory by the β factor, related to the bias factor and the growth rate via: 1.8.27\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\beta (z,k) = {{{\Omega _m}{{\left(z \right)}^{\gamma (k,z)}}} \over {b(z)}}\,.$$\end{document} The derivative of the redshift distortion parameter with respect to the sound speed is: 1.8.28\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{\partial \log (1 + \beta {\mu ^2})} \over {\partial \log c_s^2}} = - {3 \over {5 - 6w}}{{\beta {\mu ^2}} \over {1 + \beta {\mu ^2}}}{x \over {1 + x}}(Q - 1)\,.$$\end{document} We see that the behavior versus \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$c_s^2$\end{document} is similar to the one for the Q derivative, so the same discussion applies. Once again, the effect is maximized for small cs. The β derivative is comparable to that of G at z = 0 but becomes more important at low redshifts.
Shape of the dark matter power spectrum
Quantifying the impact of the sound speed on the matter power spectrum is quite hard as we need to run Boltzmann codes (such as camb, [559]) in order to get the full impact of dark-energy perturbations into the matter power spectrum. [786] proceeded in two ways: first using the camb output and then considering the analytic expression from [337] (which does not include dark energy perturbations, i.e., does not include cs).
They find that the impact of the derivative of the matter power spectrum with respect the sound speed on the final errors is only relevant if high values of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$c_s^2$\end{document} are considered; by decreasing the sound speed, the results are less and less affected. The reason is that for low values of the sound speed other parameters, like the growth factor, start to be the dominant source of information on \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$c_s^2$\end{document}.

Impact on weak lensing. Now it is possible to investigate the response of weak lensing (WL) to the dark-energy parameters. Proceeding with a Fisher matrix as in [41], the main difference here being that the parameter Q has an explicit form. Since Q depends on w and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$c_s^2$\end{document}, we can forecast the precision with which those parameters can be extracted. We can also try to trace where the constraints come from. For a vanishing anisotropic stress the WL potential becomes: 1.8.29\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${k^2}(\Phi + \Psi) = - 2Q{{3H_0^2{\Omega _{M,0}}} \over {2a}}{\Delta _M}$$\end{document} which can be written, in linear perturbation theory as: 1.8.30\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${k^2}(\Phi + \Psi) = - 3H{(a)^2}{a^3}Q(a,k)\;{\Omega _M}(a)\;G\;(a,k){\Delta _M}(k)\,.$$\end{document}

Hence, the lensing potential contains three conceptually different contributions from the dark-energy perturbations:

The direct contribution of the perturbations to the gravitational potential through the factor Q.
The impact of the dark-energy perturbations on the growth rate of the dark matter perturbations, affecting the time dependence of ΔM, through G (a, k).
A change in the shape of the matter power spectrum P (k), corresponding to the dark energy induced k dependence of ΔM.
