A general likelihood function for a future experiment (subscript i) can be Taylor-expanded around its maximum-likelihood value, μi. By definition, at the maximum the first derivatives vanish, and the shape of the log-likelihood in parameter space is approximated by the Hessian matrix Hi, 5.2.9\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
