In order to carry out the optimization procedure, it might be useful to adopt a principal component analysis (PCA) to determine a suitable parametrization of w (z) [468, 838]. The redshift range of the survey can be split into N bins, with the equation of state taking on a value wi in the i-th bin: 5.3.1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$w(z) = \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {{w_i}} {b_i}(z).$$\end{document} where the basis functions bi are top-hats of value 1 inside the bin, and 0 elsewhere. If F is the Fisher matrix for the N parameters wi, one can diagonalize it by writing F = WT ΛW, where Λ is a diagonal matrix, and the rows of W are the eigenvectors ei (z) or the so-called principal components. These define a new basis (in which the new coefficients αi are uncorrelated) so the equation of state can be written as 5.3.2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$w(z) = \sum\limits_{i = 1}^N {{\alpha _i}} {e_i}(z).$$\end{document} The diagonal elements of Λ are the eigenvalues λi and define the variance of the new parameters, σ2(αi) = 1/λi.

